problems.problem_fmt:
Find the <b>perimeter</b> of the following rectilinear figure.<br>
<br>
<img src="//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/6/6/4/66438f280b2da91f683e0e972bf92da892147371.png" class="asy-image"  width="218" height="212" alt="[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

draw((0,2)--(0,10)--(6,10)--(6,7)--(10,7)--(10,0)--(8,0)--(8,2)--cycle);

label(&quot;$8$&quot;, (3,10), N);
label(&quot;$4$&quot;, (6,17/2), E);
label(&quot;$5$&quot;, (8,7), N);
label(&quot;$10$&quot;, (10,7/2), E);
[/asy]">

problems.solution_text:
The sum of the two red vertical lengths must be equal to $4 + 10 = 14.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

draw((0,2)--(0,10)--(6,10)--(6,7)--(10,7)--(10,0)--(8,0)--(8,2)--cycle);
draw((0,7)--(6,7),dashed);
draw((8,2)--(10,2),dashed);
draw((0,2)--(0,10), red + linewidth(2*bp));
draw((8,0)--(8,2), red + linewidth(2*bp));

label("$8$", (3,10), N);
label("$4$", (6,17/2), E);
label("$5$", (8,7), N);
label("$10$", (10,7/2), E);
[/asy]

Similarly, the sum of the two blue horizontal lengths must be $8 + 5 = 13.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

draw((0,2)--(0,10)--(6,10)--(6,7)--(10,7)--(10,0)--(8,0)--(8,2)--cycle);
draw((6,2)--(6,7),dashed);
draw((8,2)--(8,7),dashed);
draw((0,2)--(8,2), blue + linewidth(2*bp));
draw((8,0)--(10,0), blue + linewidth(2*bp));

label("$8$", (3,10), N);
label("$4$", (6,17/2), E);
label("$5$", (8,7), N);
label("$10$", (10,7/2), E);
[/asy]

Therefore, the perimeter of the figure is $14 + 14 + 13 + 13 = \boxed{54}.$

problems.problem_fmt:
Find the <b>area</b> of the following rectilinear figure.<br>
<br>
<img src="//latex.artofproblemsolving.com/c/8/6/c866c3b8376e7342e2adf89e6a97f639edbacf21.png" class="asy-image"  width="275" height="208" alt="[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

draw((0,0)--(0,3)--(6,3)--(6,7)--(10,7)--(10,5)--(7,5)--(7,0)--cycle);

label(&quot;$8$&quot;, (3,3), N);
label(&quot;$7$&quot;, (6,5), W);
label(&quot;$7$&quot;, (8,7), N);
label(&quot;$2$&quot;, (10,6), E);
label(&quot;$5$&quot;, (17/2,5), S);
label(&quot;$9$&quot;, (7,5/2), E);
label(&quot;$10$&quot;, (7/2,0), S);
label(&quot;$4$&quot;, (0,3/2), W);
[/asy]">

problems.solution_text:
[b]Solution 1[/b]. We can dissect the figure into three rectangles, which have dimensions $8 \times 4,$ $2 \times 11,$ and $5 \times 2.$  Thus, the area is
\[8 \times 4 + 2 \times 11 + 5 \times 2 = \boxed{64}.\]

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

draw((0,0)--(0,3)--(6,3)--(6,7)--(10,7)--(10,5)--(7,5)--(7,0)--cycle);
draw((6,3)--(6,0),dashed);
draw((7,5)--(7,7),dashed);

label("$8$", (3,3), N);
label("$7$", (6,5), W);
label("$2$", (6.5,7), N);
label("$5$", (17/2,7), N);
label("$2$", (10,6), E);
label("$5$", (17/2,5), S);
label("$9$", (7,5/2), E);
label("$8$", (3,0), S);
label("$2$", (6.5,0), S);
label("$4$", (0,3/2), W);
[/asy]

[b]Solution 2[/b]. We can start with a $15 \times 11$ rectangle, and cut out an $8 \times 7$ rectangle and a $5 \times 9$ rectangle.  Thus, the area of the figure is
\[15 \times 11 - 8 \times 7 - 5 \times 9 = \boxed{64}.\]

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

draw((0,0)--(0,3)--(6,3)--(6,7)--(10,7)--(10,5)--(7,5)--(7,0)--cycle);
draw((0,3)--(0,7)--(6,7),dashed);
draw((7,0)--(10,0)--(10,5),dashed);

label("$8$", (3,3), N);
label("$7$", (6,5), W);
label("$7$", (8,7), N);
label("$2$", (10,6), E);
label("$5$", (17/2,5), S);
label("$9$", (7,5/2), E);
label("$10$", (7/2,0), S);
label("$4$", (0,3/2), W);
[/asy]

It helps to draw a picture:
[asy]
size(6cm);
pair a=(0,0); pair b=(sqrt(3),sqrt(6)); pair c=(sqrt(3)+sqrt(30),0);
pair d=((sqrt(3)+sqrt(30))/2,-sqrt(31-6*sqrt(10))/2);
dot(a); dot(b); dot(c); dot(d);
draw(a--b--c--d--a);
draw(a--c,dashed);
label("3",(a+b)/2,NW);
label("6",(b+c)/2,NE);
label("4",(c+d)/2,SSE);
label("4",(d+a)/2,SSW);
label("?",0.6*a+0.4*c,N);
label("$A$",a,W);
label("$B$",b,N);
label("$C$",c,E);
label("$D$",d,S);
[/asy]
The picture above is not necessarily to scale; the length marked as $\text{``?''}$ can be varied by "flexing" the edges of the quadrilateral. We want to find all possible values for $\text{``?''}$.

Remember that the triangle inequality tells us that the sum of any two sides of the triangle is greater than the third side.  Applying this to triangle $ABC,$ we obtain the inequalities
\begin{align*}
AB + AC &> BC, \\
AB + BC &> AC, \\
AC + BC &> AB.
\end{align*}
Since $AB = 3$ and $BC = 6,$ these inequalities become
\begin{align*}
3 + AC &> 6, \\
3 + 6 &> AC, \\
AC + 6 &> 3.
\end{align*}
The first inequality $3 + AC > 6$ tells us that $AC > 6 - 3 = 3.$  The second inequality tells us that $AC < 9.$  And the third inequality $AC + 6 > 3$ holds for any value of $AC$ (since it is positive), so it does not give us any information.  So now we know that $AC$ must satisfy $3 < AC < 9.$

We can then apply the triangle inequality to triangle $ADC,$ which gives us
\begin{align*}
AC + AD &> CD, \\
AC + CD &> AD, \\
AD + CD &> AC.
\end{align*}
Since $AD = CD = 4,$ these inequalities become
\begin{align*}
AC + 4 &> 4, \\
AC + 4 &> 4, \\
4 + 4 &> AC.
\end{align*}
The inequality $AC + 4 > 4$ holds for any value of $AC,$ so it does not give us any information.  The third inequality $4 + 4 > AC$ tells us that $AC < 8.$

So now we know that $AC$ must satisfy both $3 < AC < 9$ and $AC < 8.$  The only integers that satisfy both conditions are $\boxed{4,~5,~6,~\text{and }7}$.
